    text: "What is the defining principle of a zero-trust network?",
    options: ["Monitoring all egress traffic", "Using cryptographic erase", "Continually verifying requests for resources", "Implementing network security groups"],
    answer: 2,
    explanation: "Continually verifying requests for resources Zero trust is a widely adopted model for securing cloud environments in which traditional perimeter defenses are insufficient. Zero trust assumes no user or device is inherently trustworthy, so every access attempt must be authenticated, authorized, and validated continuously. Monitoring of all egress traffic is not the defining characteristic of zero trust. Implementation of network security groups is an access control mechanism, but it does not inherently define zero trust. Cryptographic erase is a data sanitization method. Practical Cloud Security: A Guide for Secure Design and Deployment, 2nd Edition (ISBN: 978-1098148171). Pg 3. The Official",
