    answer: 2,
    explanation: "Federation Cloud customers often need to extend their existing IAM systems into the cloud so that users can authenticate seamlessly without separate credentials. A federation allows a CSP to integrate with a customer’s IAM system, often through standards like SAML or OAuth, to avoid creating duplicate accounts in the cloud provider’s system and to support single sign-on across environments. Privilege access management focuses on controlling and auditing the use of elevated or administrative accounts. Role-based access control manages permissions within a system but does not handle identity federation with external IAM systems. Multifactor authentication strengthens user verification by requiring multiple credentials, but it does not integrate CSPs with an existing IAM system. Practical Cloud Security: A Guide for Secure Design and Deployment, 2nd Edition (ISBN: 978-1098148171). Pg 57-60. The Official",
