    explanation: "A systems administrator needs to install a new application on a server. Cloud identity and access control is an important security concept. Configuration changes or system-level modifications, such as installing a new application on a server, generally require administrative or root-level permissions. This is considered privileged access and is handled with a command such as sudo (superuser do). A microservice needing its own account to store data on a system is a service account, which may not require privileged access. A user needing to log into a remote system to access some documents is standard user access. Physical access to a system in a data center that has become inaccessible through the network is not digital privileged access. Practical Cloud Security: A Guide for Secure Design and Deployment, 2nd Edition (ISBN: 978-1098148171). Pg 57-58. The Official",
