    id: 155,
    text: "How does cryptographic erase prevent the disclosure of data?",
    options: ["By", "storing", "the encrypted data on an airgapped system By overwriting the encrypted data with random values By encrypting the data with multiple keys", "By destroying the keys needed to decrypt the data"],
    answer: 3,
    explanation: "By destroying the keys needed to decrypt the data Cryptographic erase works by making encrypted data permanently unreadable when the encryption keys are securely destroyed. Since the ciphertext cannot be decrypted without the keys, the data is effectively unrecoverable even though the physical storage may still contain the encrypted data. Secure deletion of data is critical in shared environments, and cryptographic erase provides a way to ensure that data cannot be recovered after decommissioning. Encrypting the data with multiple keys would only complicate key management. Storing the encrypted data on an airgapped system does not guarantee permanent inaccessibility if the encryption keys still exist. Overwriting the encrypted data with random values is traditional data wiping, not cryptographic erase. Practical Cloud Security: A Guide for Secure Design and Deployment, 2nd Edition (ISBN: 978-1098148171). Pg 28. The Official",
