    explanation: "Web application firewall (WAF) Protecting web-based applications from malicious traffic is critical in cloud environments where most services are delivered through HTTP and HTTPS. A WAF inspects and filters HTTP and HTTPS traffic, detecting malicious activity such as SQL injection, cross-site scripting, and other attacks targeting web applications. A database activity monitoring (DAM) tool focuses on monitoring queries and database transactions, not analyzing incoming HTTP or HTTPS traffic. An Extensible Markup Language (XML) firewall specifically protects XML-based transactions, which is not a general defense for all web traffic. An application programming interface (API) gateway secures and manages APIs, but it does not provide comprehensive protection against general malicious HTTP and HTTPS attacks. Practical Cloud Security: A Guide for Secure Design and Deployment, 2nd Edition (ISBN: 978-1098148171). Pg 148. The Official",
