    id: 1264,
    text: "Why do snapshot backups have unique security considerations?",
    options: ["They cannot be transferred off the system where they originated. There", "is no way to determine whether their integrity has been compromised.", "They do not carry the same access control permissions as the system", "they were taken from. They are always stored in an unencrypted format."],
    answer: 2,
    explanation: "They do not carry the same access control permissions as the system they were taken from. Snapshots are widely used for quick recovery, but they can expose sensitive data if not properly managed. Snapshots often bypass or fail to inherit fine-grained access controls from the source system, which means sensitive data may be accessible to users who would not normally have permission. Snapshots can usually be exported, migrated, or replicated across systems or cloud regions. Snapshots can still be checked for integrity using hashing, checksums, or built-in validation tools. Many cloud platforms support encryption for snapshots. The Official",
