    explanation: "Audit scope restrictions By clearly defining and limiting the scope of the audit, an organization ensures the audit examines only agreed-on areas. This prevents auditors from expanding coverage beyond what is necessary and keeps costs predictable. A gap analysis identifies differences between current practices and requirements. SOC 1 Type II reports are outputs of an audit, not a way to manage costs. External audit controls do not directly prevent scope creep.The Official",
